{"name":"Wolfgang - The Enslaved Pharmacist","type":"npc","img":"icons/magic/nature/root-vine-entangled-humanoid.webp","system":{"npcType":"villager","oppositionLevel":3,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"Wolfgang is not a real druid—he's a pharmacist from a nearby town who was kidnapped by Helga for his knowledge of herbs and medicines. He's forced to serve her under the threat that she'll kill his family if he disobeys. He maintains the animated forest trap by sprinkling blood at the roots of the trees. Wolfgang appears in druidic robes holding a wooden staff, but his nervous demeanor betrays his true nature. He desperately wants to escape Helga's control but feels trapped by his situation. If the Hunters promise to free him and protect his family, he can provide valuable information about the village layout, safe paths through the forest, and Helga's plans. He knows about the Infusion of Purity—a potion that can break blood magic curses—but Helga won't let him include elderberry in the recipe, claiming it's too rare. The truth is that a complete Infusion would break her control over him and the other servants.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":1,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I'm a simple pharmacist forced to pretend to be a druid","Helga threatens my family if I don't obey","I hate what I've become, but I don't know how to escape","I know herbs and medicines, not magic"],"gifts":[],"conditions":[],"notes":"Wolfgang can be a valuable ally if the Hunters gain his trust. He knows: the recipe for Infusion of Purity (burdock, nettle, hyssop, elderberry), safe paths through the animated forest, the layout of Helga's mansion, and that elderberry is the key ingredient Helga forbids. If freed from blood magic control, he'll help the Hunters escape and provide medical assistance."},"_id":"0a7ec963e1d9206a"}
{"name":"Henrich - The Worried Father","type":"npc","img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","system":{"npcType":"villager","isMainNPC":false,"oppositionLevel":3,"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":1,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am a simple farmer who loves his son more than anything","I will do whatever it takes to help him, even if it means venturing into a village full of monsters"],"agenda":["Find help for my son Klaus who suffers from ozena","Protect my son from harm"],"gifts":[],"background":"Henrich is a simple farmer whose adult son Klaus suffers from ozena—a terrible disease that has destroyed his nose. They heard rumors that Margareta Westen, the Good Witch of Gelb, might be able to help. When they arrived in Gelb, they were terrified by the sight of so many deformed and disfigured people living there. Henrich is nervous but determined to help his son, even if it means facing his fears.","notes":"Minor NPC encountered on the road to Gelb. If the Hunters are kind and offer to help, Henrich agrees to guide them to the village. If they threaten or intimidate him, he runs away. Lowe the Coward is observing this encounter from a distance, judging the Hunters' character.","conditions":[]},"flags":{"scenario":"Ozena Part One - The Yellow Village","inspiration":"The Wizard of Oz","role":"Worried father seeking help for his afflicted son"},"_id":"7451a3ee4db6787a"}
{"name":"Klaus - The Afflicted Son","type":"npc","img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","system":{"npcType":"villager","isMainNPC":false,"oppositionLevel":3,"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":1,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I suffer from ozena, a disease that has destroyed my nose and made me hideous","I keep my face covered because I cannot bear to see the disgust in people's eyes"],"agenda":["Find a cure or relief from my terrible affliction","Hide my shame from others"],"gifts":[],"background":"Klaus is the adult son of farmer Henrich. He suffers from ozena—the same disease that afflicts Dorothea/OZena—a terrible condition that has destroyed his nasal cavity, leaving his face disfigured. He is deeply ashamed of his appearance and keeps his face covered at all times. He and his father heard that Margareta Westen might be able to help, but when they saw Gelb's inhabitants, they became frightened and fled. Klaus becomes a pawn in OZena's plans when he is kidnapped by Hirnloser and Dose to lure the Hunters into a trap.","notes":"Klaus is kidnapped shortly after midnight by Hirnloser and Dose, who carry him into the swamp west of Gelb. He is used as bait to test the Hunters and force a confrontation. His fate depends on how the Hunters handle the situation—showing compassion may save him and start redeeming OZena's companions.","conditions":[]},"flags":{"scenario":"Ozena Part One - The Yellow Village","inspiration":"The Wizard of Oz","role":"Victim who shares OZena's affliction, becomes kidnapping target"},"_id":"b926728b9e811d12"}
{"name":"Villagers of Emerald - Wish-Warped Souls","type":"npc","img":"icons/magic/symbols/question-stone-yellow.webp","system":{"npcType":"villager","oppositionLevel":3,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"The Villagers of Emerald were once ordinary people living in Smaragd. When Dr. Henkle arrived and cured their epidemic, they hailed him as a savior. He discovered a magical wishing well in the nearby forest and encouraged villagers to make wishes. Each wish was granted—but in the most literal, horrifying way possible. A villager who wished for wealth now spits gold coins and bile. One who wished for beauty has a body that constantly warps and shifts trying to achieve impossible standards. A child who wished to grow up became a giant with a child's mind. Two lovers who wished to never be apart were merged into one body. Now these wish-warped souls serve Henkle, believing he'll eventually fix everything if they're loyal. They're tragic figures—ordinary people whose desires were twisted into nightmares. They attack intruders to Smaragd not out of malice but out of desperation and false hope. If the wishing well is destroyed or if Henkle is defeated, some may gradually return to normal, while others remain permanently transformed. Each encounter with Villagers of Emerald should emphasize the tragedy—these were regular people (farmers, merchants, children, parents) who made understandable wishes and paid terrible prices.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":1,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I was an ordinary villager who made a wish at the well","My wish was granted, but not in the way I hoped","Now I am a monster","I serve the wizard who promised to fix everything"],"gifts":[{"name":"Careful What You Wish For","description":"Each Villager of Emerald has been transformed by their wish. Roll 1d6+1 to determine: **1-Wealth:** Spits 1d6 gold coins at enemies, hitting up to 3 targets within 15ft, each hit inflicts 1 Wound, also vomits bile constantly. **2-Beauty:** Body constantly warps and shifts, anyone looking suffers 1 Penalty on Checks due to disturbing sight. **3-Health:** Cannot die or stay injured, regenerates 1 Wound at start of each Exchange, only defeated by destroying well or reversing wish. **4-Skill:** Supernaturally skilled at profession, OL increases to 5, performs craft obsessively even in combat. **5-Never Sleep:** Cannot sleep, exhausted and manic, chatters nonsense constantly, speech causes 1 Penalty on concentration Checks. **6-Grow Up:** Child with giant body but childish mind, has 3 Wounds total, inflicts +1 Wound damage, cries and tantrums during combat. **7-Love:** Merged with beloved into one body, can act twice per Exchange, argue constantly about what to do (if convinced to stop, both stop)."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"Villagers of Emerald typically appear in groups of 3-5 with different wishes. Emphasize the tragedy—they're victims, not villains. If Henkle is defeated or the well destroyed, many may revert to normal or at least stop serving him. Smart Hunters can use persuasion to convince wish-warped villagers that Henkle won't fix them. The ones who wished for health are particularly difficult as they regenerate constantly. Roll for each villager encountered to create variety."},"_id":"c5ac2032b8636881"}
{"name":"Porcelain Dolls - Blood-Bound Servants","type":"npc","img":"icons/equipment/head/mask-carved-scream-tan.webp","system":{"npcType":"villager","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"The Porcelain Dolls are twelve servants bound by Helga's blood magic, each wearing a porcelain mask and carrying a different weapon. They stand perfectly still in the village square around the Porcelain Princess, moving only when she commands. These were once ordinary villagers from Rot who fell under Helga's control through blood magic rituals. Now they serve as the Princess's elite guard, their individual personalities and wills suppressed by the enchantment. Each Doll carries one of six weapon types: spears (attack from 10 feet), double weapons (attack twice), great blades (+1 Wound), whips (disarm opponents), poisoned blades (victim takes 1 Wound next Exchange), or shields (+1 Defense). When combat begins in the village square, mind-controlled villagers complicate the battlefield by getting in the way. If the Infusion of Purity is splashed on the Dolls, they're freed from blood magic and either flee in panic or turn on the Princess, confused and terrified. Behind their masks, they're just ordinary people forced to commit terrible acts. Their voices sometimes break through the enchantment with pleas for help or expressions of horror at what they're being made to do.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":1,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["We are the blood-bound servants","Our wills are not our own","We move only when commanded","Behind the masks we are just ordinary people"],"gifts":[{"name":"Armed Guard","description":"Each Porcelain Doll carries one of six weapon types (roll 1d6 to determine): **1-Spear:** Can attack from 10 feet away. **2-Double Weapon:** Can attack twice in one Exchange. **3-Great Blade:** Inflicts 1 additional Wound on successful hit. **4-Whip:** Can disarm opponents (contested Check). **5-Soaked Weapon:** Poisoned blade—victim takes 1 Wound at start of next Exchange. **6-Shield:** Has +1 Defense against physical attacks."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"There are twelve Porcelain Dolls total, but they typically don't all attack at once. Roll 1d6 for each Doll encountered to determine their weapon type. The Dolls fight with mechanical precision but no creativity—they follow the Princess's commands exactly. If freed from blood magic control (via Infusion of Purity), they panic and flee or provide information about Helga's mansion layout. Some may beg the Hunters to save their families who are also held captive in Rot."},"_id":"fec576c2edc608ea"}
